The team captained by ^*BRoy Welland^*N of New York won the team event at this year's Cavendish. The rest of the winning team consisted of Roy's partner ^*BBjorn Fallenius^*N (originally from Sweden and now living in New York),  ^*BBridge Base Inc.^*N President ^*BFred Gitelman^*N (Toronto, Canada), Fred's partner ^*BBrad Moss^*N (New York), and ^*BHoward Weinstein-Steve Garner^*N (Chicago).

Roy and Bjorn capped off a great tournament by finishing a very strong 3rd in the Cavendish Pairs. This week's deal features a hot defense that this pair found in the second session of this event. Their opponents were 2 of the greatest players in the world today, ^*BGeir Helgemo^*N of Norway and ^*BSam Lev^*N, originally from Israel, but now living in New York.

Fred and Brad went on a very exciting ride during the Cavendish Pairs. They scored poorly in the first 2 sessions which left them in 41st place (out of 52 pairs) at that point of the event. Fred and Brad proceeded to post the top score in the next 2 sessions to climb all the way to 1st place. That was fun! Unfortunately, the last session was not as much fun as Fred and Brad slipped to 8th place, a reasonable showing, but this result was pretty disappointing for Fred and Brad given their standing going into the last session.

The winners of the 2001 Cavendish Invitational Pairs were ^*BMichel Kwiecien^*N and ^*BJacek Pszczola^*N of Poland. This pair has performed very well in several major tournaments during the past few years and in our view they are one of the very best pairs in the world right now. Some of the others partnerships in this category are also Polish - Poland has truly become a superpower of world bridge.

